data.content:
Here are the improved MSTest assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User)); // if type-checking
    // For predicate checks, use a filtered comparison:
    var inactive = users.Where(u => !u.IsActive).ToList();
    Assert.AreEqual(0, inactive.Count, "Expected all users to be active");

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x == y)` | `Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, list.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Contains(x))` | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, x)` |

**Why switch?** `Assert.AreEqual` and `Assert.IsNotNull` produce meaningful failure messages (e.g., "Expected: 3, Actual: 1") instead of just "Assert.IsTrue failed."

Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods: `AreEquivalent` (same items, any order), `IsSubsetOf`, `AllItemsAreUnique`, and `AllItemsAreNotNull`.
